<section class="assessment-overview">
  <div class="container">
    <h2>Understanding Negotiation Styles</h2>
    <p>
      Negotiation styles represent patterns in how individuals approach conflict, make decisions, and interact with others during negotiations. Your style is influenced by your personality, experiences, cultural background, and the specific context of each negotiation.
    </p>
    <p>
      While most people have a dominant style they default to, effective negotiators can adapt their approach based on the situation, relationship, and counterpart. This assessment will help you identify your natural tendencies and develop greater flexibility.
    </p>
    
    <div class="style-framework">
      <h3>The Five Negotiation Styles</h3>
      <p>This assessment is based on a framework that identifies five distinct negotiation styles:</p>
      
      <div class="styles-grid">
        <div class="style-card">
          <h4>Competing</h4>
          <p><strong>Approach:</strong> Assertive and uncooperative, focused on achieving own goals</p>
          <p><strong>When effective:</strong> Crisis situations, when unpopular actions are necessary, when quick decisions are needed</p>
          <p><strong>Potential drawbacks:</strong> May damage relationships, overlook creative solutions, create resistance</p>
        </div>
        
        <div class="style-card">
          <h4>Accommodating</h4>
          <p><strong>Approach:</strong> Unassertive and cooperative, focused on preserving relationships</p>
          <p><strong>When effective:</strong> When the issue is more important to the other party, when preserving harmony is critical</p>
          <p><strong>Potential drawbacks:</strong> May sacrifice important interests, create resentment, encourage exploitation</p>
        </div>
        
        <div class="style-card">
          <h4>Avoiding</h4>
          <p><strong>Approach:</strong> Unassertive and uncooperative, focused on postponing or sidestepping conflict</p>
          <p><strong>When effective:</strong> When issues are trivial, when emotions are high, when more information is needed</p>
          <p><strong>Potential drawbacks:</strong> May leave important issues unresolved, create frustration, miss opportunities</p>
        </div>
        
        <div class="style-card">
          <h4>Collaborating</h4>
          <p><strong>Approach:</strong> Assertive and cooperative, focused on finding solutions that satisfy all parties</p>
          <p><strong>When effective:</strong> When both sets of concerns are too important to compromise, when creative solutions are possible</p>
          <p><strong>Potential drawbacks:</strong> May be time-consuming, inappropriate for simple issues or urgent situations</p>
        </div>
        
        <div class="style-card">
          <h4>Compromising</h4>
          <p><strong>Approach:</strong> Moderately assertive and cooperative, focused on finding middle ground</p>
          <p><strong>When effective:</strong> When goals are moderately important, when parties have equal power, when time is limited</p>
          <p><strong>Potential drawbacks:</strong> May result in suboptimal solutions, focus on positions rather than interests</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

